1
00:00:13,764 --> 00:00:14,765
[elevator bell dings]

2
00:00:16,517 --> 00:00:18,519
[wind howling]

3
00:00:35,077 --> 00:00:36,203
[Irving echoing] Hello!

4
00:00:41,291 --> 00:00:42,751
Hello!

5
00:00:49,591 --> 00:00:50,592
[Mark] Irving!

6
00:00:52,719 --> 00:00:55,305
- It's me. I'm up here!
- Mark!

7
00:00:55,889 --> 00:00:57,139
[Mark] Yeah!

8
00:00:57,140 --> 00:00:58,225
Hey!

9
00:01:00,686 --> 00:01:02,770
[stammers] What's happening?

10
00:01:02,771 --> 00:01:04,104
Where are we?

11
00:01:04,105 --> 00:01:10,904
[Mark] I have no fucking idea, but there's a path up the cliff right down there!

12
00:01:12,573 --> 00:01:14,199
[Irving] Do you
want me to come up?

13
00:01:15,534 --> 00:01:16,869
[Mark] Well, yeah!

14
00:01:19,830 --> 00:01:22,039
[Irving] I'm on...
[groans] I'm on the ice.

15
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:23,792
I'm on the fucking ice!

16
00:01:24,418 --> 00:01:26,795
[Mark] Maybe get
off of it. Come on!

17
00:01:33,594 --> 00:01:34,595
[Irving] I'm coming!

18
00:01:36,096 --> 00:01:37,346
[groaning, panting]

19
00:01:37,347 --> 00:01:39,224
[ice crackling]

20
00:01:41,310 --> 00:01:42,477
[grunts] I'm...

21
00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:45,479
I'm coming!

22
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:46,773
Be careful!

23
00:01:50,861 --> 00:01:53,322
[Irving groans, panting]

24
00:02:01,079 --> 00:02:02,706
[Mark] It's very steep!

25
00:02:05,542 --> 00:02:08,169
[grunting, panting]

26
00:02:19,806 --> 00:02:20,807
[grunts]

27
00:02:22,267 --> 00:02:23,560
[pants, sniffs]

28
00:02:24,061 --> 00:02:26,480
- [grunts, sighs]
- [Helly] Irving.

29
00:02:27,314 --> 00:02:28,524
[Irving] Helly!

30
00:02:30,526 --> 00:02:31,860
Where did you come from?

31
00:02:32,402 --> 00:02:33,694
I don't know.

32
00:02:33,695 --> 00:02:35,113
What are we doing out here?

33
00:02:35,864 --> 00:02:37,324
[Mark] Up here!

34
00:02:38,033 --> 00:02:40,744
Follow my voice!

35
00:02:43,247 --> 00:02:44,248
Mark!

36
00:02:44,998 --> 00:02:47,167
[Irving grunting]

37
00:02:48,961 --> 00:02:49,962
Mark!

38
00:02:50,629 --> 00:02:52,130
[Mark] Up here!

39
00:02:55,592 --> 00:02:56,843
[Irving] Mark.

40
00:02:56,844 --> 00:02:58,261
[Mark] Hey!

41
00:02:58,262 --> 00:02:59,346
Are you okay?

42
00:03:00,222 --> 00:03:01,889
- Did you wake up on the ice too?
- Yeah.

43
00:03:01,890 --> 00:03:04,225
- What about you?
- On the cliff.

44
00:03:04,226 --> 00:03:09,063
- [Dylan screams, grunting]
- [Irving] Oh, my God.

45
00:03:09,064 --> 00:03:11,357
- Is it you?
- [Helly] Of course it's us.

46
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:12,860
Holy shit!

47
00:03:13,527 --> 00:03:15,612
Out-fucking-side.

48
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:21,243
Oh, my God. I mean, I knew
there was no actual ceiling, but this is fucking insane.

49
00:03:22,661 --> 00:03:23,662
Hello?

50
00:03:25,205 --> 00:03:26,832
Hello?

51
00:03:29,459 --> 00:03:32,212
[electronic Kier hymn playing]

52
00:03:35,757 --> 00:03:36,800
[Mark] What is that?

53
00:03:45,684 --> 00:03:47,686
[music continues]

54
00:04:26,975 --> 00:04:27,976
[music stops]

55
00:04:30,604 --> 00:04:32,231
Good morning, Refiners.

56
00:04:33,232 --> 00:04:42,991
This is Mr. Milchick from work,
and I'm thrilled to welcome you to your first ever outdoor retreat and team-building occurrence.

57
00:04:44,243 --> 00:04:49,831
This ORTBO is in response to your
desire to see the outside world.

58
00:04:50,374 --> 00:05:01,593
With your outies' blessings, you will spend the next two calendar days walking the meadows, thickets, brambles and brooks that make up the Dieter Eagan National Forest.

59
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:05,222
Who the fuck is Dieter Eagan?

60
00:05:07,933 --> 00:05:09,226
Dieter Eagan?

61
00:05:10,102 --> 00:05:12,896
Some of you may be quietly
yearning to learn more.

62
00:05:13,772 --> 00:05:17,860
The truth you seek lies
within the fourth appendix.

63
00:05:19,111 --> 00:05:28,287
Kier dictated a fourth appendix
in his final hours of life, a text of such sanctity that it is forbidden upon the severed floor.

64
00:05:29,621 --> 00:05:38,839
It's waiting for
you in Scissor Cave, the very same grotto where Kier Eagan tamed the four tempers for the very first time.

65
00:05:39,965 --> 00:05:47,681
And do remember, "Stray not from Kier's path, lest you roil nature's wrath."

66
00:05:50,225 --> 00:05:52,060
There will be help
along the way.

67
00:05:54,855 --> 00:05:56,481
Happy fortunes, MDR.

68
00:05:57,691 --> 00:05:58,692
[beeps]

69
00:06:04,990 --> 00:06:06,325
Scissor Cave.

70
00:06:17,127 --> 00:06:18,462
What the fuck is that?

71
00:06:28,847 --> 00:06:30,974
He looks like Mark.

72
00:06:42,903 --> 00:06:46,073
Milchick said there'd
be help along the way.

73
00:06:46,865 --> 00:06:50,076
I wouldn't trust a word out
of that mountebank's mouth.

74
00:06:50,077 --> 00:06:51,537
Not even televisually.

75
00:07:05,634 --> 00:07:08,512
Not like we have a lot of
other options right now, Irv.

76
00:09:14,638 --> 00:09:15,848
[sighs]

77
00:09:48,297 --> 00:09:49,298
Wait.

78
00:10:33,008 --> 00:10:34,301
[Helly] "Chapter one.

79
00:10:36,678 --> 00:10:38,514
I was not born into
this world alone.

80
00:10:39,765 --> 00:10:45,062
The lodgings of my mother's
womb I shared with another, a twin brother who was called Dieter."

81
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:48,732
Kier had a twin?

82
00:10:50,651 --> 00:10:52,486
That's what those things are.

83
00:10:53,237 --> 00:10:54,279
[Irving] Yeah.

84
00:10:55,572 --> 00:11:03,705
"In infancy, he was my bosom friend.
But as we blossomed into boyhood, he beseeched me to take to the wood with him to live as paupers.

85
00:11:05,249 --> 00:11:12,172
My love for my twin
unbalancing my judgment, I acceded, and we ventured into the wood towards"...

86
00:11:14,466 --> 00:11:15,968
[both] "Woe's Hollow."

87
00:11:23,183 --> 00:11:28,647
[Irving] So, we're to walk
in the brothers' footsteps.

88
00:11:33,026 --> 00:11:36,780
"He always crept like
this at this hour.

89
00:11:37,823 --> 00:11:43,661
- Once concealed by flora, my brother"...
- [Kier] ...flora, my brother unfastened himself.

90
00:11:43,662 --> 00:11:50,752
The din of his fervor fell strangely
into concert with the music of the wood.

91
00:11:51,461 --> 00:11:57,258
His every thrust found rhythm - with the trill of the crickets... - "trill of the crickets"...

92
00:11:57,259 --> 00:12:00,139
- and the moaning of the wind...
- "and the moaning of the wind"...

93
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:04,015
- and the snowfall's yearly thaw.
- "and the snowfall's yearly thaw."

94
00:12:04,016 --> 00:12:09,312
[Kier] Dieter
became, on that night - an instrument of nature... - [Irving] ..."an instrument of nature"...

95
00:12:09,313 --> 00:12:12,982
- and nature played Dieter...
- "and nature played Dieter with elegance.

96
00:12:12,983 --> 00:12:20,449
I had no choice but to listen as he spilt his lineage upon the soil."

97
00:12:43,222 --> 00:12:44,556
Now there's a me one.

98
00:13:12,334 --> 00:13:14,586
[sniffs, breathes heavily]

99
00:13:22,469 --> 00:13:24,221
[panting]

100
00:13:28,767 --> 00:13:29,810
You okay?

101
00:13:31,103 --> 00:13:32,104
[sighing] Yeah.

102
00:13:33,063 --> 00:13:35,065
I just wish I knew
where we were going.

103
00:13:38,610 --> 00:13:39,611
[exhales sharply]

104
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:44,240
[breathing heavily]

105
00:13:44,241 --> 00:13:46,952
[no audible dialogue]

106
00:13:50,622 --> 00:13:53,542
[panting]

107
00:13:59,423 --> 00:14:00,424
[Dylan] Fuck.

108
00:14:24,406 --> 00:14:27,284
What were you and Helly
talking about back there?

109
00:14:33,040 --> 00:14:34,041
[Dylan groans]

110
00:14:37,044 --> 00:14:38,045
When?

111
00:14:39,713 --> 00:14:41,673
I don't trust her.

112
00:14:42,674 --> 00:14:45,969
I think she might be lying
about what her outie saw.

113
00:14:46,553 --> 00:14:47,804
Why would you think that?

114
00:14:48,514 --> 00:14:50,516
Night gardeners. Hmm?

115
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:56,020
[sighs] It's clear you do not
have an objective perspective due to your feelings for her.

116
00:14:56,021 --> 00:14:59,191
My feelings for her have nothing
to do with anything, okay...

117
00:15:05,739 --> 00:15:07,365
[Dylan sniffs, sighs]

118
00:15:07,366 --> 00:15:08,450
[Mark] Whoa.

119
00:15:20,754 --> 00:15:22,130
What the fuck?

120
00:15:25,008 --> 00:15:26,301
What is it?

121
00:15:27,219 --> 00:15:28,220
I don't know.

122
00:15:29,596 --> 00:15:32,015
Looks like a seal.

123
00:15:37,062 --> 00:15:38,856
Why does it look so messed up?

124
00:15:40,774 --> 00:15:43,443
I don't know. Maybe this is
what dead things look like.

125
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:47,281
We should eat it.

126
00:15:48,282 --> 00:15:49,282
Pardon me?

127
00:15:49,283 --> 00:15:51,618
We don't know if there's
food waiting at the hollow.

128
00:15:52,828 --> 00:15:54,954
We don't even know where we are.

129
00:15:54,955 --> 00:15:56,915
They can't let
anything happen to us.

130
00:15:57,499 --> 00:15:58,457
It's an ORTBO.

131
00:15:58,458 --> 00:16:01,878
Outdoor retreat team-building
occurrence. Right, Mark?

132
00:16:01,879 --> 00:16:03,630
We don't know what this is.

133
00:16:04,590 --> 00:16:07,593
- We don't know anything!
- Irving, calm down.

134
00:16:09,136 --> 00:16:12,138
We all know you had a bad experience
the last time you were outside...

135
00:16:12,139 --> 00:16:14,599
Who said I had a bad experience?

136
00:16:14,600 --> 00:16:15,809
Oh, my God.

137
00:16:17,895 --> 00:16:19,645
What did you tell him, dumbass?

138
00:16:19,646 --> 00:16:22,482
Nothing! What the fuck?

139
00:16:23,775 --> 00:16:25,611
Let's just get to the hollow.

140
00:17:19,957 --> 00:17:22,041
[Mr. Milchick] Kier's
twin was always with him.

141
00:17:24,419 --> 00:17:27,047
That's why we provided the
very same for each of you.

142
00:17:28,131 --> 00:17:30,091
Fuck you all. I was right.

143
00:17:30,092 --> 00:17:31,426
Mr. Milchick.

144
00:17:32,594 --> 00:17:35,138
This is the tallest
waterfall on the planet.

145
00:17:37,140 --> 00:17:42,437
You have followed the path of Kier
and Dieter, and reached Woe's Hollow.

146
00:17:43,772 --> 00:17:45,482
You stand upon sacred earth.

147
00:17:47,442 --> 00:17:49,069
We're starving, Mr. Milchick.

148
00:17:50,362 --> 00:17:51,363
Are you?

149
00:17:52,948 --> 00:17:55,492
I thought the waterfall's
grandeur would satiate you.

150
00:17:59,413 --> 00:18:01,123
I'm teasing, of course.

151
00:18:02,416 --> 00:18:04,751
Lumon will always
protect and provide.

152
00:18:05,878 --> 00:18:06,879
Right this way.

153
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:12,110
Miss Huang has been readying the grill for
which we brought in copious luxury meats.

154
00:19:14,112 --> 00:19:17,199
The fire will be used for
marshmallows and a recital later.

155
00:19:18,200 --> 00:19:26,458
The tents, as you
can see, are MDR blue and the outhouse is stocked with four-ply washroom tissue.

156
00:19:28,627 --> 00:19:29,627
Wow.

157
00:19:29,628 --> 00:19:32,089
[Mr. Milchick chuckles]
Wow, indeed, Helly R.

158
00:19:33,674 --> 00:19:41,765
Also, for your comfort
and safety, torches, which can provide both a heat and a light source.

159
00:19:43,267 --> 00:19:44,268
Double duty.

160
00:19:46,061 --> 00:19:47,563
It's beautiful.

161
00:19:49,857 --> 00:19:51,233
Pretty cool, right?

162
00:19:54,111 --> 00:19:56,154
Yes, lovely.

163
00:19:59,825 --> 00:20:00,826
[grunts]

164
00:20:02,411 --> 00:20:03,412
[Helly] Irving?

165
00:20:03,912 --> 00:20:04,913
Enter.

166
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:09,001
[sighs]

167
00:20:11,086 --> 00:20:12,546
- [Helly shivers]
- Hmm.

168
00:20:18,594 --> 00:20:20,053
Made you a snow seal.

169
00:20:23,682 --> 00:20:24,766
[chuckles]

170
00:20:27,561 --> 00:20:28,979
In case you were hungry.

171
00:20:29,938 --> 00:20:31,522
[chuckles]

172
00:20:31,523 --> 00:20:32,608
Yeah.

173
00:20:33,525 --> 00:20:38,613
I feel silly for suggesting
we eat that animal.

174
00:20:38,614 --> 00:20:43,659
I suppose it sounded
alarmist and paranoid.

175
00:20:43,660 --> 00:20:44,702
Irrational.

176
00:20:44,703 --> 00:20:47,831
No. It was fine. We
were all a little...

177
00:20:50,709 --> 00:20:51,710
[sighs]

178
00:20:54,755 --> 00:20:55,756
Yeah.

179
00:21:03,305 --> 00:21:06,683
What did you really see during
the overtime contingency?

180
00:21:14,191 --> 00:21:15,192
I told you.

181
00:21:17,611 --> 00:21:18,612
[Irving] It's okay.

182
00:21:20,113 --> 00:21:21,573
It won't change anything.

183
00:21:31,291 --> 00:21:32,292
Irving.

184
00:21:43,929 --> 00:21:45,222
Okay.

185
00:21:47,057 --> 00:21:49,059
[theremin playing]

186
00:22:06,618 --> 00:22:12,332
[Mr. Milchick] "Dieter lay
unwashed in his bedroll, though the hollow's pool was primed for bathing.

187
00:22:13,417 --> 00:22:19,381
We ate of the hare we'd caught and told each other rhyming jokes till our gullets ached.

188
00:22:20,632 --> 00:22:25,345
But at last, the thought
tickling my mouth emerged.

189
00:22:26,763 --> 00:22:29,224
'We must return to
Father, ' I said.

190
00:22:30,225 --> 00:22:32,936
'But I promise to look after
you in the ether mill.'

191
00:22:34,479 --> 00:22:39,276
When at last a sound came from
him, it was a bewailing whimper.

192
00:22:39,985 --> 00:22:44,990
He believed, I suppose, that
we'd be woodland paupers forever.

193
00:22:48,911 --> 00:22:51,330
I was looking at him
when his eye came out.

194
00:22:52,122 --> 00:22:59,213
It popped from the socket, driven by a sudden torrent of pus from his skull.

195
00:23:01,715 --> 00:23:09,389
And he reached up to
grasp at his hair, which was suddenly moss that tore easily from his bleeding scalp."

196
00:23:10,349 --> 00:23:11,599
Good heavens.

197
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:26,532
[Mr. Milchick] "And as the pus
from his eye thickened into sap, I turned from my gargling brother and walked to the pool of the hollow, where I knew the waterfall would drown out my brother's cries."

198
00:23:28,116 --> 00:23:29,409
That's actually really smart.

199
00:23:30,118 --> 00:23:41,713
"And it was here that I first
encountered the temper Woe, a gaunt bride, half the height of a natural woman.

200
00:24:00,649 --> 00:24:06,738
She spoke to me directly
from her eyes and said, 'This is your doing.

201
00:24:08,115 --> 00:24:10,742
You suffered his wantonness.

202
00:24:12,160 --> 00:24:14,162
Now he's no one's brother.

203
00:24:15,247 --> 00:24:28,760
Only chaos's whore.'" The end.

204
00:24:35,392 --> 00:24:38,645
Perhaps in the morning, we'll
have time for the next chapter...

205
00:24:39,855 --> 00:24:42,524
"Kier and the Thieving Nanny."

206
00:24:43,525 --> 00:24:45,569
- [Helly] Hmm. Creepy.
- Whoa.

207
00:24:47,738 --> 00:24:51,283
Did his brother really die
that way, Mr. Milchick?

208
00:24:54,745 --> 00:24:58,457
The handbook enriches our work
with tales of the founder's life.

209
00:25:00,334 --> 00:25:01,709
Every word is truth.

210
00:25:01,710 --> 00:25:02,794
[Helly sputters]

211
00:25:04,713 --> 00:25:09,175
[laughs] I'm sorry. Sorry.

212
00:25:09,176 --> 00:25:10,260
Helly.

213
00:25:10,802 --> 00:25:13,430
[laughing continues] What?

214
00:25:17,976 --> 00:25:21,020
- [Mr. Milchick] Helly R.?
- You guys... [laughs]

215
00:25:21,021 --> 00:25:23,231
He melted, right? [sniffles]

216
00:25:23,232 --> 00:25:25,691
He turned into the forest
because he masturbated.

217
00:25:25,692 --> 00:25:28,194
[both laughing]

218
00:25:28,195 --> 00:25:31,280
I mean, seriously, that's actually
the dumbest thing I've ever heard.

219
00:25:31,281 --> 00:25:36,745
- [Mark laughing]
- [Dylan chuckles] Right? He jerked off in front of his brother...

220
00:25:37,913 --> 00:25:40,414
and he got punished for it.

221
00:25:40,415 --> 00:25:43,042
[Mark laughing] Wha...
You can't say that.

222
00:25:43,043 --> 00:25:45,920
- [Helly] He just said it. [laughs]
- [Mark] Wha... [laughs] He did.

223
00:25:45,921 --> 00:25:49,424
[stammers] I... It's... It's...

224
00:25:51,593 --> 00:25:54,555
You know, we often laugh at
what we don't understand.

225
00:25:59,518 --> 00:26:02,729
The team I thought I knew would
have processed more thoughtfully.

226
00:26:06,316 --> 00:26:07,317
Miss Huang.

227
00:26:11,405 --> 00:26:12,823
The marshmallows, please.

228
00:26:22,374 --> 00:26:24,001
Throw them in the fire.

229
00:26:24,585 --> 00:26:30,632
- [gasps] Mr. Milchick, come on.
- [Helly scoffs] Now, Miss Huang.

230
00:26:34,386 --> 00:26:37,347
- [Helly, laughing] Oh, my...
- [Mark gasps] Why?

231
00:26:38,640 --> 00:26:41,602
Marshmallows are for
team players, Dylan.

232
00:26:42,561 --> 00:26:44,354
They don't just hand them out.

233
00:26:50,235 --> 00:26:51,236
What?

234
00:26:54,281 --> 00:26:55,282
Good night.

235
00:27:04,666 --> 00:27:05,751
Wow.

236
00:27:06,543 --> 00:27:11,047
- [Mark] Oh, my God.
- [Helly laughs] Hey, what do you think his dick turned into?

237
00:27:11,048 --> 00:27:14,593
[laughing]

238
00:27:17,221 --> 00:27:18,347
[Dylan chuckles]

239
00:27:19,681 --> 00:27:20,932
It isn't funny.

240
00:27:20,933 --> 00:27:26,062
- Oh, I don't know. It's pretty funny.
- [Helly laughs] - [Irving] Well, it's not. - Okay.

241
00:27:26,063 --> 00:27:28,941
And stop making
goo-goo eyes at her.

242
00:27:29,483 --> 00:27:34,403
- [laughs] I'm not.
- [laughs] Stop.

243
00:27:34,404 --> 00:27:40,077
- "Goo-goo eyes"?
- [Helly laughs] Just tell us, Helly.

244
00:27:41,161 --> 00:27:42,703
[scoffs] What?

245
00:27:42,704 --> 00:27:44,288
[Mark] Come on. Tell us.

246
00:27:44,289 --> 00:27:46,375
